    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Uniforms for school children, which are often made mandatory. School uniform designs vary, but may consist of a jacket and a skirt or a pair of pants, a collared shirt and a type of neckwear. Originally these may have been inspired by formal wear, military, or marine uniforms.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000105512/Davidson, Blazers, Badges and Boaters: A Pictorial History of School Uniform (1990)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Uniform voor schoolgaande kinderen, zoals dit in bepaalde landen, op sommige scholen, verplicht is of is geweest. Meestal bestaande uit een jasje en rok of broek, overhemd en een bepaalde soort halsbedekking. Geïnspireerd op formele kleding, soms militaire of marine-uniformen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
